<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#000000">Strategy</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"> I Bid 2-3 burdens at the beginning. It doesn&#39;t matter whether I go first or not. If my opponent outbids me, I get to use my shadow sites to do  damage with my Nazgul. I chose Weathertop because I&#39;m playing with some twilight Nazgul and they&#39;ll all be fierce there in the event that I draw some. If I happen to outbid my opponent, I&#39;ll go first and use the Prancing Pony to pull Aragorn and usually run to site 3. If I get in trouble or am really unlucky at site 2, I&#39;ll stop, let my opponent pass me onto site 3, and play the Ford. The shadow side of the deck<br>
 is designed to slow down my opponent and prevent him from moving twice during his turn.    Occasionally, I&#39;m able to kill the ring-bearer.  It wants to be found and twilight Nazgul add burdens which makes Dark Whispers and  Nazgul swords very effective. The twilight Witch-King is very good for adding burdens, also.<br>
     The Free Peoples side is designed to run to site 9. I use &quot;Trust me as you once did&quot; and Gandalf to pump up Aragorn and Gimli in combat.   Along with his weapons and Last Alliance, Aragorn can defeat  anything short of the Balrog. Gimli is at least a 9, 11 with his axe and he can exert to add two to his strength<br>
so he won&#39;t lose many skirmishes either. If things get sticky, Frodo himself has the Gandalf signet and can take advantage of Trust Me to survive a skirmish. Power According to his stature is always great against Moria swarms, particularly in the late game, and Gandalf himself has up to 6 vitality to ensure his staying around for awhile and making sure trust me remainsuseful.<br>
<br>
